Using the equation in Step 4, the value of equity is solved below: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Value of Equity}&=\$1,065-\left[\frac{\$1,000}{\left(1+0.039\right)}\right]\\[20pt]
&=\$1,065-\left(\frac{\$1,000}{1.039}\right)\\[20pt]
&=\$1,065-\$962.46\\[20pt]
&=\boxed{\$102.54}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, the value of equity is $102.54.

The value of debt is solved below: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Value of Debt}&=\text{Value of Assets}-\text{Value of Equity}\\[15pt]
&=\$1,065-\$102.54\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{962.46}
\end{aligned}$$

The value of the asset is subtracted by the computed value of equity to determine the value of debt. 

Hence, the value of the debt is $962.46.

Now, we are going to solve the interest of the debt: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Interest}&=\text{FV of Debt}-\text{Value ofDebt}\\[15pt]
&=\$1,000-\$962.46\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\$37.54}
\end{aligned}$$

The computed value of debt is deducted from the debt's face value to determine the interest. 

Therefore, the interest is $37.54.

After solving the interest, the interest rate is solved below: 


&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Interest Rate}&=\left(\frac{\text{Interest}}{\text{FV of Debt}}\right)\times100\\[20pt]
&=\left(\frac{\$37.54}{\$1,000}\right)\times100\\[20pt]
&=0.03754\times100\\[20pt]
&=\boxed{3.754\%}
\end{aligned}$$


The quotient of interest and face value of the debt is multiplied by 100 to determine the debt's interest rate. 

Thus, the interest rate of debt is 3.754%.

Let us solve the value of equity using the 20% risk free rate: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Value of Equity}&=\$1,065-\left[\frac{\$1,000}{\left(1+0.20\right)}\right]\\[20pt]
&=\$1,065-\left(\frac{\$1,000}{1.20}\right)\\[20pt]
&=\$1,065-\$833.33\\[20pt]
&=\boxed{\$231.67}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, the value of equity is $231.67 if the risk-free rate is $231.67.
